# What is Scripta?

Scripta is an app for creating, editing, and publishing articles with beautiful things like this

| image figure:1
https://imagedelivery.net/9U-0Y4sEzXlO6BXzTnQnYQ/83fdbf6c-79d5-44e7-6ac6-00cdc7785000/public

and this

| equation
pdd(u,x) + pdd(u,y) + pdd(u,z) = frac(1,c^2) pdd(u,t)

[i The equation above governs the transmission of light from sun to flower to the eye of the beholder as in Figure 1] .

[b What we aim to do.] (1) Provide a tool that makes it easy to write short notes with images and equations — for yourself, your friends and colleagues, or for the class you are teaching. Becuase Scripta.io is a web-based platform, it is easy to "publish" your writing. One way to do this is to provide a link to your document. As an example, the link for this document is

| indent
https://scripta.io/g/jxxcarlson:welcome-to-scripta.1

Paste it into your browser and you will see that it works. The [code /g/ ] means that anyone using this link is automatically signed in as a guest — a user with limited privileges A guest cannot, for example create documents.

(2) Provide what you need to write longer work: multi-section articles and books.

(3) Any Scripta document can be printed to PDF (see the printer icon) and can be exported to LaTeX. [gray By exporting your document and adding custom style files, you can satisfy the requirements of your publisher.]

[b Example:] Here is the [link PDF file https://pdfserv.app/pdf/jxxcarlson-id-c60a3d8c-ad17-4770-adfd-54080dc5689c.pdf] for this document.

## The Scripta Language

The scripta language consists of just two things, [index elements] and [index blocks] . [footnote Our aim is to design a langauge that is as simple as possible without losing expressive power.]

### Elements

Ordinary text, like "Happy New Year" is an element. So is [code [i Happy New Year] ] . This is an [index italic element] . It renders as [i Happy New Year] . The [index bold element] looks like [code [b Happy New Year] ] . I renders as you would expect, [b Happy New Year] . Thus [code [i [b Happy New Year]] ] yields [i [b Happy New Year]] . You can also do things like [code [red [i Happy New Year]] ] to get [red [i Happy New Year]] .

You can write mathematical formulas, equations, etc. using a [index math element] , e.g., [m a^2 + b^2 = c^2] . Here is what we wrote: [code [math a^2 + b^2 = c^2] ] . The shorthand form [code [m a^2 + b^2 = c^2] ] also works. If you want, you can use TeX/LaTex syntax, [code $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$ ] .

For code, you can use a [index code element] . Thus [code a^2 + b^ = c^2 ] is produced by writing [code [code a^2 + b^ = c^2] ] . You can also enclose code in backticks, e.g., [bt ] a^2 + b^2 = c^2 [bt ] .

### Other elements

Below are some elements of note. There are many more — for a complete list and a fuller explanation, see XXX.

- [code [strike this text] ] [m \to] [strike this text] .
- [code [highlight this text] ] [m \to] [highlight this text]
- [code [index atom] ] adds "atom" to the document index. Use an index block to display the index.
- Use [code [cite einstein1905a] ] to cite the reference einstein1905a in the bibliography. Use a bibref block to make the actual reference. Example: In 1905, Albert Einstein published three ground-breaking papers: [cite einstein1905a] , [cite einstein1905b] , [cite einstein1905c] . The first was instrumental in the development of quantum mechanics, the second in the atomic theory of matter. The third introduce the special theory of relativity and the famous equation [m E = mc^2] .

### Blocks

| image expandable caption:Jellyfish float:left width:70
https://imagedelivery.net/9U-0Y4sEzXlO6BXzTnQnYQ/5c12dfcf-0698-4e0b-733b-f9abf2bfff00/public

| paragraph padding-right:3
The tiny image of jellyfish that you see on your left is put there using an [index image block] . Click on the image to expand it. Click on the expanded image to return the view you ser here. Image blocks have a lot of options. Lets begin with the simplest case, no option at all:

| code
| image
https://imagedelivery.net/9U-0Y4s...

It has the form

| code
HEADER
BODY

In this case, the header is the single line [code | image ] . The body is the line [code https://imagedelivery.net... ] — the "internet address" of the image.

The image block we used above is a little more complex:

| code
| image expandable 
| float:left 
| width:70 
| caption:Jellyfish
https://imagedelivery.net/9U-0Y4s...

In this case the header consists of four lines, each beginning with the pipe symbol "|" followed by a space. The first line of the header is "| image expandable". Here "expandable" is an [index argument] . These are single words that change the behavior of the image block. In the case at hand, it means that if you click on the image it pops to fill a much larger screen. Clicking the expanded image returns it to its normal state. There can be more than one argument, but these always come before the properties.

The next line of the header is the text "float:left". It defines a [index property] of the image block. Properties are defined by text of the form [code key:value ] . In this case the key is "float" and the value associated with that key is "left". A block with this property hugs the left margin of the document and the text below it flows around it. There is also a [code float:right ] property. The properties set by the next two lines define the width in pixels of image displayed and its caption.

### Math Blocks
  Here is a very simple [index math block] :

| code
| math
a^2 + b^2 = c^2

It yields this:

| math
a^2 + b^2 = c^2

We can add a [index label] property to it:

| code
| math label:pythag
a^2 + b^2 = c^2

| math label:pythag
a^2 + b^2 = c^2

Any math block that has the label property is automatically numbered. The label can be used with the [index mathref] element to refer back to the equation as in the paragraph below:

| indent
Equation [mathref pythag] is the [i Pythagorean theorem] , where [m a] and [m b] are the lengths of the legs of a right triangle, and [m c] is the length of the hypotenuse.

Click on the reference one to go to equation (1). Press ESC to return to where you were. The mathref element we used here is [code [mathref pythag] ] .

[i For LaTeX users:] As a convenience, Scripta provides [index equation blocks] and [index eqref elements] . These are synomyms for math blocks and mathref elements. They corresond to equation environments and eqref macros in LaTeX.

### Chemistry Blocks

Chemical formulas and reactions can be rendered using [index chem elements] and [index chem blocks] . The formula for methane is [chem CH4 ] . Burning hydrogen in oxygen takes place fia the reaction [chem 2H2 + O2 -> 2H2O + Energy ] .

To produce the text above, we used

| code
[chem CH4] and [chem 2H2 + O2 -> 2H2O + Energy]

See [link The mhchem bundle by Martin Hensel https://texdoc.org/serve/mhchem/0] for a comprehensive discussion of what you can do with chem elements and blocks. These blocks relie on mhchem.

### Code Blocks

Below is an example of a [index code block]

| code lang:python
  def is_prime(n):
      if n < 2:
          return False
      for k in range(2, int(n**0.5) + 1):
          if n % k == 0:
              return False
      return True
  
  
  def print_primes_up_to(N):
      for p in range(2, N + 1):
          if is_prime(p):
              print(p)
  
  
  # example usage
  N = 100
  print_primes_up_to(N)

