## Exceptional Blocks

Some blocks have an off-beat syntax. For sections, subsections, etc., we borrow from Markdownk using hashmarks [code # ] . The skeleton of an article might be

| code
  | title
  The Kingdoms of Life
  
  # Archaea
  
  # Bacteria
  
    ## Proteobacteria
    
    ## Cyanobacteria
  
  # Protista
  
  # Fungi
  
  # Plantae

Itemized and numbered lists are also exceptional blocks, again inspired by Markdown. Here is an itemized list:

| code
  - Milk
  
  - Cookies
  
  - Paper plates

It renders as

- Milk

- Cookies

- Paper plates

Numbered lists are written as

| code
  . Milk
  
  . Cookies
  
  . Paper plates

Itrenders like this:

. Milk

. Cookies

. Paper plates


# Ergonomic

Scripta is desiged to be ergonomic. When you write mathematical text, for example,

| equation numbered
frac(sin theta_1, sin theta_2) = frac(v_1, v_2)

you write

| code
| equation numbered
frac(sin theta_1, sin theta_2) = frac(v_1, v_2)

instead of the usal TeX:

| code
| equation
\frac{\sin\theta_1}{\sin\theta_2} = \frac{v_1}{v_2}

The notation is, for he most part, like the notation in mathematics. Relatively few backslashes and curly braces. If you wish, however, you can use the second, standard LaTeX form. We call streamlined syntax [i ETeX] , for [quote Ergonomic TeX.]

| mathmacros
pd:       frac(partial #1, partial #2)      
pdd:      frac(partial^2 #1, partial #2^2)  

